{
  "response_text": "The average weekly consumption of skimmed and semi-skimmed milk per agent initiates at approximately 5.29 units at time step 0, representing the 1974 baseline when whole milk dominated market preferences. A phase of rapid adoption ensues, with consumption increasing significantly through time step 11, where it reaches approximately 1265.47 units. This early period exhibits statistically robust upward trends, with particularly steep ascents recorded in the intervals spanning steps 0\u20134 and 5\u20139, corresponding to the initial diffusion of low-fat milk alternatives through the social network.\n\nFollowing this initial growth, the system enters an extended plateau phase persisting from approximately step 11 through step 27. During this middle period, consumption stabilizes around a median value of roughly 1220 units, exhibiting oscillatory behavior rather than sustained monotonic trends. The metric fluctuates between local minima of approximately 1183.39 units (step 18) and local maxima near 1265.47 units (step 11), with additional peaks at step 13 (1240.35), step 19 (1221.57), and step 21 (1226.86), and intervening valleys at step 12 (1233.62), step 20 (1214.46), and step 23 (1209.70). Statistical tests confirm the absence of significant trends in rolling windows covering steps 10\u201324, indicating a dynamic equilibrium with a dominant oscillation cycle of approximately 15 time steps. This plateau suggests a saturation point where habit formation and social influence mechanisms stabilize choice functions near a high-consumption regime.\n\nA final growth phase emerges from step 27 to step 32, characterized by a statistically significant increasing trend with a slope of 48.544 units per step. Consumption rises from approximately 1200\u20131220 units to a terminal value of 1456.60 units at step 32. This late-stage intensification suggests renewed disposition triggers or shifting social norms that overcome incumbent habit thresholds, driving the system toward near-complete adoption of skimmed and semi-skimmed varieties by the conclusion of the simulation period in 2005.\n\nThe trajectory\u2014minimal initial adoption, rapid diffusion, prolonged saturation with cyclical variations, and terminal intensification\u2014demonstrates how perception thresholds, habit persistence, and social network effects interact to produce non-linear dietary transitions. The oscillatory patterns during the plateau phase particularly highlight the role of cognitive dissonance and justification mechanisms in creating temporary fluctuations around a stable high-adoption equilibrium, while the final surge indicates that sustained social influence eventually overwhelms residual preference inertia for whole milk."
}

